bib.title: One-Neutron Transfer Reactions With Beryllium, Carbonand Oxygen Nuclei.

free_txt: The solid state detectors, areas 10 mm*40 mm,
whose apertures are determined by collimators in front
of them and whose angular positions and radial
distances are adjustable to +-0.03 adeg. and + - 1 mm
respectively were used. The reaction solid angle in the
laboratory system is determined by the aperture of
detector one, detector two merely being placed close
enough to the target to detect all particles whose
reaction partners have entered detector one. In most
cases the first counter aperture is 2 mm*30 mm and its
distance from the target 400 mm.

Error from the graphic bars
Differential cross sections were obtained with a
general precision of between +-7% and 15%, as indicated
by the error bars. In addition, the overall
normalisation is determined to about +-10%.
The targets are a few tens of mu-g/cm2 thick and 10 mm
diameter, with a very thin layer of gold evaporated on
the surface for purposes of beam normalisation.
The Be-9 targets are made by subliming a layer of
beryllium on to a carbon foil backing of approximately
5 mu-g/cm2 so that the beryllium does not overlap the
metal support. Foils prepared in this way are about
20 mu-g/cm2 thick and stand up well to handling
stresses and beam irradiation.
